‚Äã@@jazz3006 you have a legitimate point. is saving a life truly worth it if it means one does not truly live? at what point is it not worth it to gain happiness or satisfaction in life if it risks one's self or others? the answers to the questions are truly subjective and based off of one's own experiences, and how much safety or freedom they are willing to forsake for the other. life truly is a gambling game. whether you bet high or low is of one's personal opinion. however, everyone rolls the dice for other people all the time, and affecting other people without their consent is a reoccurring theme in politics (some conservatives wanting to ban abortions and non-heterosexual marriages, conservatives claiming liberals wanting to ban firearms and "being able to pray in schools"). however, freedom vs. safety tradeoffs are much less black and white. i apologize for attacking you, if you perceived my admittedly rude comment as such. i came into this comment section less prepared than i should have, and i thank you on offering a calm, logical, and intelligent response to my hasty accusation. i truly appreciate the new outlook on life, and revealing that others with dissenting opinions can have logical arguments and reasonings to back up their judgement. also i've been debating religious extremists and anti-vaxxers for a while so my standards have been set low.

tldr; 
i'm sorry for being rude, you sparked a large paradigm shift for me, and i've realized empathy for people such as you who are being and will be forced to give up parts of their lives. i am grateful you responded  with reasoning and logic instead of fighting my fire with your own fire. i truly need to think things through before i say them. i'm sorry for potentially wasting your time, but i just felt like sharing your impact on my view of the world. how absurd that this all happened because i naively assumed that "other opinions are wrong." thank you.

@veritasium 
because you tried to write off criticism of self driving as being limited to absurd trolley problems, while completely glossing over the facts that;
1. we already live in a world where ai/ml is under-regulated to the point that 'black box' algorithms are making healthcare and financial decisions that kill people, while those responsible simply shrug their shoulders and say they don't understand how the software works, and
2. uber's competing self-driving vehicles have already killed a pedestrian, and the only real action taken (other than uber making sure the press knew that the person was homeless and crossing the street improperly - as if the punishment for jaywalking should be death, and the lives of the poor and vulnerable should be valued less) was a software patch, and an assurance from a company, that already killed a pedestrian with a vehicle they claimed was safe enough to be trusted in their community, that it wouldn't happen again.

i'd like to pose you the question: would you volunteer to take responsibility if your self driving car killed someone in the process of making this video? if not, who would you shirk that responsibility to?

nevermind decisions about whether we should kill motorcyclists with or without helmets, or weighing the value of life of two old people against one young person. until we're mature enough to create a system of actual accountability for the decisions of an algorithm in the first place, these companies have no place setting the tone for the future of transport in our communities, and the message of your video is tremendously irresponsible.
